  footnotes: []
english:
  title: On the Same Occasion
  author: Jeong Cho
  language: eng
  text: |-
    At ninety, my mother still maintains her vigor and health.
    On this clear day, fine screens unfold in the high hall.
    Colored silks upon her person shimmer with pure joy.
    Golden chalices raised in hand to bless her lengthened years.
    The sounds of silk and music fill the front pavilion,
    While servants in their finest adornments line the rear courtyard.
    I, orphaned early, now wear white upon my head—
    Witnessing your good fortune, I cannot hold back my tears.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'golden chalice' refers to ceremonial wine cups used in celebrations of longevity, particularly those honoring elderly parents.
  - key: ''
    value: The contrast between the speaker's early loss of parents and the occasion being celebrated creates the poignant emotional core of the poem.
  - key: ''
    value: White hair is a traditional symbol of both age and mourning in East Asian poetry.
